      <hedline>
        <hl1>Wind and Sea</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eric Rosenbloom letter on Susan Allen Toth's July 11 article notes possibility that wind turbines will be erected on Lewis Island, Scotland</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: Susan Allen Toth describes both the relentless wind and the consuming silence on the Hebrides island of Lewis (''A Remote, Ancient Isle,'' July 11).</p>
        <p>Renewable energy developers also have noted the wind and are threatening the island's serenity with a proposed wind ''farm'' using the largest available turbines and towers.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: Susan Allen Toth describes both the relentless wind and the consuming silence on the Hebrides island of Lewis (''A Remote, Ancient Isle,'' July 11).</p>
        <p>Renewable energy developers also have noted the wind and are threatening the island's serenity with a proposed wind ''farm'' using the largest available turbines and towers.</p>
        <p>The British and Scottish governments fully support the project, which will be among the biggest in the world and will provide at most only 0.5 percent of the U.K.'s electricity. A 400-mile undersea power cable is being planned to connect the Hebrides to the coast of Wales, so this is likely to be but the first in a long series of such projects.</p>
        <p>ERIC ROSENBLOOM  Kirby, Vt.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
